        <name>L7.2 Q2 Improper integral 1</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;Compute the improper integral. If it convergent evaluate it, otherwise enter the value &lt;code&gt;none&lt;/code&gt; as your answer. \[ I = \int_{{@alaraja@}}^{{@ylaraja@}} \textrm{e}^{-x} {@b@} \, \textrm{d}x. \] \( I = \) [[input:SAns]][[validation:SAns]]
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Give your answer in exact form.&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>We have the integral: \[ I = \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} {{@b@}} \, \textrm{d}x.\] We can use integration by parts: \(\displaystyle\int_a^{b} u(x)v'(x) \, \textrm{d}x = [u(x)v(x)]_a^b -\int_{a}^{b} u'(x)v(x) \, \textrm{d}x\)&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;We have: \(u(x)=\textrm{e}^{-x} \Rightarrow u'(x)=-\textrm{e}^{-x}\) and \(v'(x)= {@b@} \Rightarrow v(x)= -\frac{1}{{@a@}} \cos({{@a@}}x)\)&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So our integral becomse: \begin{eqnarray*} I = \int_{{@alaraja@}}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} {{@b@}} \, \textrm{d}x &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \bigg/_{\!\!\!\!0}^{\,\infty} -\textrm{e}^{-x} \cdot \frac{1}{{@a@}} \cdot \cos({@a@}x)-\int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \cdot \frac{1}{{@a@}}\cos({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x  \\
&amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}}-\frac{1}{{@a@}} \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \cos({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x 
\end{eqnarray*} &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Applying integration by parts again, we get:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(u(x)=\textrm{e}^{-x} \Rightarrow u'(x)=-\textrm{e}^{-x} \) and &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(v'(x)= \cos({@a@}x) \Rightarrow v(x)=\frac{1}{{@a@}} \sin({@a@}x)\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So our initial integral becomes:&lt;/p&gt;

\begin{eqnarray*} I = \frac{1}{{@a@}}-\frac{1}{{@a@}} \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \cos({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}}-\frac{1}{{@a@}} \bigg(\bigg/_{\!\!\!\!0}^{\,\infty} \frac{1}{{@a@}} \textrm{e}^{-x} \sin({@a@}x)-\int_{0}^{\infty} -\textrm{e}^{-x}\cdot \frac{1}{{@a@}} \sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x \bigg) \\
&amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}}-\frac{1}{{@a@}} \bigg( 0+ \frac{1}{{@a@}} \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \sin({{@a@}}x) \, \textrm{d}x \bigg) \\
&amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}}-\frac{1}{{@aa@}}\int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x.
\end{eqnarray*}

Whoa! The original integrand appeared also on the right hand side of the equation! Let us move it to the left side.
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x}\sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x+\frac{1}{{@aa@}} \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x}\sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}} \\
{@dd@} \int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \frac{1}{{@a@}} \\
\int_{0}^{\infty} \textrm{e}^{-x} \sin({@a@}x) \, \textrm{d}x &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; {@TAns@}.
\end{eqnarray*}&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
